Strangely enough the copy in the National Library in Berlin was formerly the property of the same Baron Muenchhausen to whom are ascribed the well known tales. Only one copy of the Latin original is held in the western hemisphere. It is in the pos- session of the Congressional Library in Washington,

The earliest translations of this diary from the original Latin text were done in Russian‚ one for Peter himself, which is full of omissions and misun- derstandings. No German translation has ever been undertaken and in French there exists only that part of the diary dealing with the revolt of the Strelitz. The English version on which the follow- ing pages are based is the only English translation, and was made by Count Macdonnell in the middle of the nineteenth century. It was published in Lon- don in 1863 and has also become comparatively rare. Charles Maedonnell‚ an Austrian Count, was de- scended from the ancient Maedonnells of Antrim, a leading branch of the Scottish elan Donnell, but he had suffered financial reverses and lived abroad.

In the preface to his translation Count Mac- donnell gives a picturesque account of the circum- stances under which he came to make it:
